<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-244-214  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 244 214.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 5 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM to reduce use of toxic chemicals.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (management).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Computer industryChemical EngineeringManufacturingPlanningHazardous Materials.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM TO REDUCE USE OF TOXIC CHEMICALS NEW YORK, NEW YORK, U.S.A., 1989 DEC 01(NB) -- International Business Machines Corporation, the world's largestmanufacturer of computers and computer products, has requested that all ofits facilities either eliminate or reduce the use of 320 chemicals classifiedas hazardous by the federal government.andM;The new policy was announced by Joseph Cascio, manager of environmentalplanning, in a November 29th speech at West Point, NY to the Hudson RiverEnvironmental Society.andP;  Cascio informed the group that a letter was beingsent to each manufacturing facility directing that a plan be developed forsubstantial reduction of the use of hazardous chemicals.andM;IBM facilities are expected to use approximately 224 million pounds ofhazardous chemicals this year with 10 million pounds (3%) being legallydisposed of in the air water and soil.andP;  Cascio said that, since the companycan do little more to reduce chemical emissions further, &quot;The only way is toeliminate use of the chemicals.&quot;andM;Cascio also told the group of another new IBM policy that requires theexplicit approval of IBM corporate headquarters in Armonk for any chemicaldischarged in a water body.andP;  The facility requesting such discharge will berequired to assess the potential environment effect of such discharge.andP;  Thisrequirement will be imposed for the discharge of any chemical, even those notcited by the government as hazardous, Cascio said.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19891201)</TEXT></DOC>